    "### Problem 2: Exploring early exponential growth rate from COVID-19 data "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this problem, you will compare the early growth rate of COVID-19 cases in the US using a simple phenomenological model and the real data.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will use the following phenomenological model\n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "C(t) = \\left [ r(1-p)t + C_0^{1-p} \\right ]^{\\frac{1}{1-p}},\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "where $C(t)$ is the cumulative number of cases as a function of time, $C_0$ is the number of cases at $t=0$, $r$ denotes the growth rate, $p$ is the \"deceleration of growth\" parameter. \n",
    "\n",
    "This model has been used to describe early epidemical growth of HIV and Ebola (see [this reference](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27451336/) for details). We would like to test whether this model captures the early rate of growth of COVID-19 cases in the US. \n",
    "\n",
    "**Part A:** Calculate rate of growth of daily cases from the data in the file `AM10-HW05-US-cases-timeseries.txt`. This file contains two columns, the first column represents days, while the second column represents the cumulative number of cases. The rate of growth of daily cases can be found by taking the first derivative of this data. Feel free to use the `central_diff` function you created in the lab. The data in this file was obtained from the [Johns Hopkins Covid-19 data repository](https://github.com/CSSEGISandData/COVID-19).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Part B:** Calculate the rate of growth of daily cases using a fit from the model, i.e., calculate $dC/dt$ using the equation above. Use the following parameters, which have been determined through a fit to the data. \n",
    "$r=0.174$, $p=0.9999$, and $C_0=1$.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Part C:** Plot the rate of growth of daily cases from part A and part B on the same figure."
   ]
  },
