    "### Problem 3: Second derivative using the three point formula\n",
    "You have already written a function that evaluates the first derivative using the central difference formula. In this problem, you have to write a function that evaluates the second derivative using the three point formula, as shown below.\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "f''(n) = \\frac{f(n+1)-2f(n)+f(n-1)}{dx^2}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "**Part A:** Write a function named `three_point_diff` that implements the above equation. The inputs to this function should be the discretized function `fx` that needs to be differentiated and the resolution `dx`. The output of this function should be the differentiated function `d2fx`.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Part B:** Now test `three_point_diff` by differentiating the function below in the range $0\\leq x\\leq 10$. Use $\\mu=5$ and $dx=0.5$. Calculate the second derivative again, this time using `central_diff` twice. \n",
    "\n",
    "\\begin{equation}\n",
    "f(x) = \\frac{1}{e^{\\mu-x} + 1}\n",
    "\\end{equation}\n",
    "\n",
    "**Part C:** Plot the results from part B (the derivatives using `three_point_diff` once and `central_diff` twice) on the same figure."
   ]
